		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/27/opinion/nyto-crimeariver/nyto-crimeariver-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/27/opinion/nyto-crimeariver/nyto-crimeariver-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/27/opinion/nyto-crimeariver/nyto-crimeariver-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002968666" width="592" height="587" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="587"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Alexander Polegenko/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/27/is-this-cold-war-ii/" data-title="âIs This Cold War II?â" data-description="Whatâs next for Russia, the United States, and Ukraine? A panel of former New York Times contributors debated the question this week. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>On Wednesday June 25, the <a href="//www.chathamhouse.org/event/russia-ukraine-and-west-confrontation-inevitable">New York Times and Chatham House convened a panel of former New York Times op-ed contributors in London</a> to debate the future of the Westâs relations with Russia in the wake of the Ukraine crisis. The panel included John Mearsheimer, a professor of political science at the University of Chicago and the author of âThe Tragedy of Great Power Politicsâ; Chrystia Freeland, a former Financial Times editor and now a member of the Canadian Parliament; Michael McFaul, the former American ambassador to Russia and now a professor at Stanford University; and Dmitri Trenin, the director of the Carnegie Moscow Center. Roger Cohen, a columnist for The New York Times, moderated. Panelists debated whether the recent crisis was caused by Vladimir Putinâs zero-sum view of geopolitics, whether the Ukrainian people will have a say in the eventual outcome and whether Russia is really a rival to the United States. An edited transcript follows.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><object id="flashObj" width="480" height="270" classid="clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000" codebase="//download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=9,0,47,0"><param name="movie" value="//c.brightcove.com/services/viewer/federated_f9?isVid=1&#038;isUI=1" /><param name="bgcolor" value="#FFFFFF" /><param name="flashVars" value="videoId=3644276726001&#038;playerID=2850193997001&#038;playerKey=AQ~~,AAACl1L7zRk~,zRhSVuSHlZRfWn2N48DuEJMjaBrbGE6V&#038;domain=embed&#038;dynamicStreaming=true" /><param name="base" value="//admin.brightcove.com" /><param name="seamlesstabbing" value="false" /><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="swLiveConnect" value="true" /><param name="allowScriptAccess" value="always" /><embed src="//c.brightcove.com/services/viewer/federated_f9?isVid=1&#038;isUI=1" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" flashVars="videoId=3644276726001&#038;playerID=2850193997001&#038;playerKey=AQ~~,AAACl1L7zRk~,zRhSVuSHlZRfWn2N48DuEJMjaBrbGE6V&#038;domain=embed&#038;dynamicStreaming=true" base="//admin.brightcove.com" name="flashObj" width="480" height="270" seamlesstabbing="false" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowFullScreen="true" allowScriptAccess="always" swLiveConnect="true" pluginspage="//www.macromedia.com/shockwave/download/index.cgi?P1_Prod_Version=ShockwaveFlash"></embed></object></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Roger Cohen:Â </strong>We meet on the eve of the 100th anniversary of the outbreak of World War I, at a time of great turbulence in Europe. Russia, by annexing Crimea, became the first major European state to annex part of another state since 1945, and since then has had a role in stirring up violence in eastern Ukraine in which several hundred people have already died. This was a shock to many people.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Prior to that annexation, we had the extraordinary and heady scenes on the Maidan in Kiev and this new state of Ukraine taking form. More recently, from newly elected President Poroshenko, there has been the offer of a ceasefire, but people continue to be killed. It appears that President Putin may be looking for an off-ramp from the violence. All this, of course, occurring at a time of American retrenchment â some say weakness.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Is President Putin looking for long-term confrontation with the West? Is this Cold War II? Is long-term confrontation really inevitable at this stage?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Chrystia, why the annexation of Crimea now and why what heâs done in eastern Ukraine at this moment?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Chrystia Freeland:Â </strong>What weâre seeing in Ukraine and in Russia is a fight about post-Soviet authoritarian kleptocracy and how sustainable that political system will be. Thatâs what Putin has decided to build in Russia. Itâs what Yanukovych was trying to build and, to everyoneâs surprise, the Ukrainians decided they didnât want it. For Putin, thatâs really dangerous, because if Ukraine â with all of its similarities to Russia â can successfully build a rule-of-law, capitalist democracy that actually works, imagine the demonstration effect in Russia. That is the core threat that Ukraine poses to Russia.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The good news, from my perspective, is that sanctions against Russia have begun to work.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Roger Cohen:Â </strong>John, you blame the United States and the West. You say that it was the expansion of NATO that essentially led Russia and President Putin to feel cornered. Is it really the West that has provoked the Russian president?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>John Mearsheimer:Â </strong>Yes. The deep and the precipitating causes of the crisis is that the West is trying to peel Ukraine away from Russiaâs orbit. In November of last year, Yanukovych said he was not going to consummate the deal with the E.U. Instead, he was going to cut an economic deal with the Russians. This led to protests, which got out of hand. On February 22<sup>nd</sup>, there was a coup, where a democratically elected leader who was for the most part pro-Russian was overthrown. It was a coup that was inextricably linked with American support for the protesters.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Immediately thereafter Putin took Crimea and has made clear that Crimea is not going to become part of NATO. He has mobilized troops on the border of eastern Ukraine. This is to tell the Ukrainians and the West that they have two choices: They can back off, or they continue to integrate Ukraine into the West, in which case heâll wreck Ukraine before he allows that to happen.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Michael McFaul:Â </strong>I was at every meeting that President Obama had either with Medvedev or Putin but one and I donât ever recall the discussion of Ukrainian membership into NATO being an issue. In the Medvedev years, we had a much different dynamic in US-Russian relations. Putin has a different worldview than Medvedev. Itâs not Russia that has a worldview; itâs Putin that believes international relations are zero-sum.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Barack Obama doesnât see the world that way. He believes in win-win outcomes and he believes that on most security and economic issues, our interests overlap with Russiaâs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Putin assigns agency to the United States that we donât have. In his eyes, Tunisia, that was us; Cairo, that was us. Syria, that was us. Russia and those people out on the streets, that was us. In Ukraine he believes the same thing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We werenât pushing for regime change in Ukraine. Ask the Ukrainians. They were incredibly disappointed with us. We were way behind. We were surprised when Yanukovych left.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But then Putin said, to hell with these guys â to hell with us. Theyâre regime-changers. Iâm going to strike back. Thatâs what Crimea was about.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Roger Cohen:</strong>Â Dmitri, youâre the man in Moscow. It would be helpful if you could describe the way Russians are thinking right now.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Dmitri Trenin:Â </strong>Overall, President Putinâs popularity has soared. Most Russians are somewhere in the middle on the crisis. They donât want their credit cards to stop working and donât want Russia to be cut off from the rest of the world, but they think the West is treating us unfairly and has always been. For most Russian people, the crisis in Ukraine is not a foreign war. For Putin, what was happening in Ukraine was a threat to Russian cultural identity.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Chrystia Freeland:</strong>Â Ukraine is now united on a sense of self, in a way that has never been before. One of the historic ironies of this situation is that when history is written, Putin is going to be the father of Ukrainian nationhood. If Putinâs goal was to hold Ukraine close to his breast, he has done absolutely the wrong thing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Roger Cohen:</strong>Â John, why shouldnât Ukraine, an independent nation and with a much stronger sense of nationhood perhaps than six months ago, make whatever decisions it wants? Why should it not be able to join the E.U.?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>John Mearsheimer:Â </strong>When youâre dealing with great powers and a country like Russia, it does not make good sense to talk about rights. Why do you expect that the Russians should accept the idea that NATO, a former military foe, can drive its alliance right up to its doorstep? In the Russiansâ eyes, it canât. International law goes out the window when a great power thinks that its core interests are at stake. Do you think we paid attention to international law when we went into Iraq in 2003? (Foolishly, I might add.) We violated international law because George Bush said explicitly that he thought core strategic interests of the United States were at stake. Thatâs whatâs going on with Ukraine.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Putin has made it very clear that Ukraine cannot join NATO. If we pursue bringing Ukraine into NATO, weâre going to wreck Ukraine.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Michael McFaul:Â </strong>I donât think Putinâs view of our agency in the world is accurate. We werenât pushing for Ukraine in NATO. We tried to argue that a strong, wealthy, stable Ukraine was in Russiaâs national interest. In the long run, the current situation makes Russia weaker.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Q&amp;A:</span></strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Q: If we look at success stories over the past century, countries like Finland and Austria that have avoided confrontation with Russia are ones that have pledged neutrality. Why hasnât that been an option that America pursued more aggressively?</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Michael McFaul:Â </strong>The assumption is that the United States was pushing for Ukraine to join NATO, and that is just not true. This has been concocted as a result of this crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>John Mearsheimer:</strong>Â What neutrality means is that Ukraine cannot be part of NATO. It cannot be a Western bulwark against Russia. Furthermore, the United States and its European allies cannot support any government in Ukraine that is decidedly anti-Russian.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Q: Where is Europe in all of this?</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Chrystia Freeland:</strong>Â For Ukrainians, geopolitics did not prompt this revolution. The revolution was about a desire to have a European-type political and economic system. Ukrainians looked across the border at Poland and said, why canât we live like that? The most important thing for Europe and for North America to do is to focus on the ninety percent of Ukraine that wants to build a prosperous, democratic market economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Dmitri Trenin:</strong>Â Russiaâs G.D.P. last year was about seventy per cent of the E.U.âs average. If youâre sitting in Kiev, you may wish to be in Munich, but you probably know that in your lifetime your G.D.P. will not reach Germanyâs level. In fact, Russiaâs G.D.P. is three times higher than Ukraineâs. And Russiaâs G.D.P. is much higher than some countries in southeastern Europe, which are members of the E.U.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A lot of Ukrainian industry is working for one market only, and thatâs the Russian market. This was a cardinal mistake of the European approach toward Ukraine.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Q: If liberal reformists fail, what would the Russian reaction be?</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Dmitri Trenin:</strong>Â Ukraine has gotten rid of a regime but the system is largely in place, sadly. I think the problem we are facing is that the post-Cold War settlement was flawed because it did not include Russia into a common security system with the West â as it did include Germany, as it did include Japan after the Second World War. That is why NATO in Ukraine is important to Putin and to the political and military establishment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Roger Cohen:</strong>Â Chrystia, if you were foreign minister, and President Putin were to continue in this aggressive nationalist vein, what would you do?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Chrystia Freeland:</strong>Â The West has given Ukraine its support and we have an obligation to help them. Itâs chiefly up to the Ukrainians whether they make it work, but we should be helping them do the institution-building and democratization they didnât do in the 1990s.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We also need to keep up the pressure on Russia without entering a new Cold War. Targeted sanctions have been effective. Putin has started to pull back. Weâre in a new phase of relationship with Russia. Itâs not a partnership, but a transactional relationship with a country that is unpredictable and frankly hostile to some of our most cherished ideals.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Finally, Europe has to sort out its energy sources. This is a long-term problem, and Canada should be helping.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Michael McFaul:</strong>Â Iâd like to end with an anecdote. The first time Obama and I met Medvedev was here, in London, April 1st, 2009. A short time before, the president of Kyrgyzstan had gone to Russia to sign a $2 billion bilateral agreement. Sometime afterwards, we got a notice that we had to close our base in Manas. Obamaâs response to Medvedev was, âHereâs the way I see it, Dmitry. Weâve got this base. Is Kyrgyzstan in our sphere of influence because of our transit center there? We spend about $60 million there, but what are we doing with that base? Weâre flying in women and men from the United States military to get a good nightâs sleep, something hot to eat, to take a shower, and then weâre sending them to forward operating bases. The people theyâre killing, if we werenât fighting them, would be fighting you. And by the way, they are fighting you, as you know dramatically from your experiences in Chechnya. So help me understand why the base is not in Russiaâs national interest.â The point the president was trying to make is that this zero-sum, 19th-century âgreat gameâ for security makes no sense.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>John Mearsheimer:</strong>Â Mike, Obama has a particular view of the world. He thinks that the Russians should share his view. Itâs a view that says geopolitics donât matter. The problem is that the Russians donât agree with him.</p>
	</div>
